00:58:42,520 --> 00:58:46,520
and which were out there as a kind of atmosphere far from the black hole,

1024
00:58:46,520 --> 00:58:50,520
which were exciting the thermometer far away.

1025
00:58:50,520 --> 00:58:53,520
And the temperature is pretty cold.

1026
00:58:53,520 --> 00:58:58,520
But in the same way, you can extrapolate downward

1027
00:58:58,520 --> 00:59:03,520
and ask what the temperature must have been close to the surface of the black hole.

1028
00:59:03,520 --> 00:59:07,520
There actually is a formula for doing it.

1029
00:59:07,520 --> 00:59:10,520
I think it's a little bit too late now.

1030
00:59:10,520 --> 00:59:12,520
Maybe we can go through it another time.

1031
00:59:12,520 --> 00:59:17,520
How you actually calculate the variation of the actual measured temperature

1032
00:59:17,520 --> 00:59:20,520
in a gravitational field.

1033
00:59:20,520 --> 00:59:23,520
But I'm going to tell you the answer.

1034
00:59:23,520 --> 00:59:27,520
The answer, first of all, is that very far away,

1035
00:59:27,520 --> 00:59:30,520
the temperature is the Hawking temperature.

1036
00:59:30,520 --> 00:59:31,520
Where is it?

1037
00:59:31,520 --> 00:59:32,520
Here it is, right over here.

1038
00:59:32,520 --> 00:59:34,520
As you get closer and closer to the black hole,

1039
00:59:34,520 --> 00:59:37,520
the temperature rises.

1040
00:59:37,520 --> 00:59:40,520
And as you get very close to the black hole,

1041
00:59:40,520 --> 00:59:45,520
as you get close to the horizon,

1042
00:59:45,520 --> 00:59:48,520
we won't call this the Hawking temperature.

1043
00:59:48,520 --> 00:59:51,520
It's kind of the extrapolated Hawking temperature,

1044
00:59:51,520 --> 00:59:53,520
which you would extrapolate into.

1045
00:59:53,520 --> 00:59:56,520
Let's give it a name, T of rho.

1046
00:59:57,520 --> 01:00:02,520
The temperature measured at a proper distance rho from the horizon,

1047
01:00:02,520 --> 01:00:08,520
it is one over two pi rho.

1048
01:00:08,520 --> 01:00:11,520
One divided by two pi rho.

1049
01:00:11,520 --> 01:00:16,520
The closer you are, the higher the temperature.

1050
01:00:16,520 --> 01:00:25,520
Now, in fact, the horizon is a very difficult place to escape from.

1051
01:00:25,520 --> 01:00:26,520
In fact, if you're behind the horizon,

1052
01:00:26,520 --> 01:00:28,520
you can't escape at all.

1053
01:00:28,520 --> 01:00:30,520
If you're right at the horizon,

1054
01:00:30,520 --> 01:00:32,520
or very close to the horizon,

1055
01:00:32,520 --> 01:00:35,520
it's extremely difficult to get away,

1056
01:00:35,520 --> 01:00:38,520
which is another way of saying you lose a lot of energy.

1057
01:00:38,520 --> 01:00:41,520
A photon loses a lot of energy

1058
01:00:41,520 --> 01:00:45,520
when it tries to escape from very close to the horizon.

1059
01:00:45,520 --> 01:00:49,520
So, if you see a finite temperature,

1060
01:00:49,520 --> 01:00:51,520
a distance above the horizon,

1061
01:00:51,520 --> 01:00:53,520
then extremely close to the horizon,

1062
01:00:53,520 --> 01:00:55,520
the kinetic energy must have been very large.

1063
01:00:56,520 --> 01:00:58,520
That's what's going on here.

1064
01:00:58,520 --> 01:01:02,520
The actual temperature of the photons,

1065
01:01:02,520 --> 01:01:04,520
or of a thermometer,

1066
01:01:04,520 --> 01:01:05,520
that would be lowered on a cable,

1067
01:01:05,520 --> 01:01:06,520
here's our experiment.

1068
01:01:06,520 --> 01:01:11,520
We're going to lower a thermometer on a cable.

1069
01:01:11,520 --> 01:01:13,520
It's going to be a tiny, tiny thermometer,

1070
01:01:13,520 --> 01:01:14,520
because for one reason or another,

1071
01:01:14,520 --> 01:01:16,520
we have to use tiny thermometers,

1072
01:01:16,520 --> 01:01:18,520
but we'll lower a tiny thermometer on a cable.

1073
01:01:18,520 --> 01:01:22,520
The cable will send back a signal

1074
01:01:22,520 --> 01:01:25,520
telling us what the temperature recorded on the thermometer is.

1075
01:01:25,520 --> 01:01:27,520
And as you lower it down,

1076
01:01:27,520 --> 01:01:29,520
you'll find the temperature goes up.

1077
01:01:29,520 --> 01:01:32,520
It goes up and up and up and up.

1078
01:01:40,520 --> 01:01:43,520
Well, if you really believed this,

1079
01:01:43,520 --> 01:01:47,520
then you would say that the temperature close to the horizon

1080
01:01:47,520 --> 01:01:49,520
was very, very hot.

1081
01:01:49,520 --> 01:01:52,520
Now, we have a funny situation now.

1082
01:01:55,520 --> 01:01:58,520
Let's suppose we take an atom

1083
01:01:58,520 --> 01:02:02,520
and we lower it down closer and closer to the horizon.

1084
01:02:02,520 --> 01:02:07,520
What happens to that atom as it gets close to the horizon?

1085
01:02:11,520 --> 01:02:14,520
Forget general relativity.

1086
01:02:14,520 --> 01:02:17,520
Now, it's just moving into a very hot region.

1087
01:02:17,520 --> 01:02:19,520
What happens to it?

1088
01:02:19,520 --> 01:02:22,520
It becomes excited.

1089
01:02:22,520 --> 01:02:24,520
But it's getting hot.

1090
01:02:24,520 --> 01:02:27,520
It's getting really, really hot.

1091
01:02:27,520 --> 01:02:29,520
It gets ionized.

1092
01:02:32,520 --> 01:02:35,520
It's getting really, really hot.

1093
01:02:35,520 --> 01:02:39,520
The nucleus gets torn to pieces by the high temperature.

1094
01:02:39,520 --> 01:02:42,520
The quarks get liberated.

1095
01:02:42,520 --> 01:02:44,520
It's defeated.

1096
01:02:44,520 --> 01:02:46,520
It's defeated. Yeah, right.

1097
01:02:46,520 --> 01:02:48,520
Well, yeah.

1098
01:02:48,520 --> 01:02:50,520
Right.

1099
01:02:50,520 --> 01:02:52,520
Yeah, that's right.

1100
01:02:52,520 --> 01:02:53,520
I mean, you know, right.

1101
01:02:53,520 --> 01:02:57,520
If we put a cable around you and lowered you down

1102
01:02:57,520 --> 01:03:00,520
and put your feet to the surface of the black hole,

1103
01:03:00,520 --> 01:03:02,520
you would get a hot foot.

1104
01:03:02,520 --> 01:03:04,520
Right.

1105
01:03:04,520 --> 01:03:06,520
That's what this picture says.

1106
01:03:06,520 --> 01:03:07,520
And how do you get away from it?

1107
01:03:07,520 --> 01:03:09,520
You've done a calculation.

1108
01:03:09,520 --> 01:03:11,520
You've done a legitimate calculation.

1109
01:03:11,520 --> 01:03:13,520
And this is a legitimate calculation.

1110
01:03:13,520 --> 01:03:15,520
I mean, the calculation is correct.

1111
01:03:15,520 --> 01:03:19,520
And by now, it's been tested over and over again.

1112
01:03:19,520 --> 01:03:22,520
If you do lower something down on a cable,

1113
01:03:22,520 --> 01:03:27,520
and then pull it back up,

1114
01:03:27,520 --> 01:03:33,520
it will give all of the evidence of having been in a very, very hot region.

1115
01:03:33,520 --> 01:03:38,520
So this is not to be questioned.

1116
01:03:38,520 --> 01:03:44,520
But there's something a little funny about this,

1117
01:03:44,520 --> 01:03:48,520
because from this point of view and from this picture over here,

1118
01:03:48,520 --> 01:03:50,520
the horizon is nothing very special.

1119
01:03:50,520 --> 01:03:51,520
It's just a green line that I've drawn.

1120
01:03:51,520 --> 01:03:53,520
It's just a green line that I drew there,

1121
01:03:53,520 --> 01:03:57,520
but there was nothing there.

1122
01:03:57,520 --> 01:04:01,520
It was just a mathematical line that I drew

1123
01:04:01,520 --> 01:04:05,520
to separate the region from which you can send a signal out to a signal

1124
01:04:05,520 --> 01:04:07,520
where you can't send a signal out.

1125
01:04:07,520 --> 01:04:09,520
But on the other hand,

1126
01:04:09,520 --> 01:04:11,520
nothing special was going on in this horizon over here.

1127
01:04:11,520 --> 01:04:14,520
The curvature didn't get large.

1128
01:04:14,520 --> 01:04:17,520
The metric near the horizon was close to flat space.

1129
01:04:17,520 --> 01:04:19,520
We've already established that.

1130
01:04:19,520 --> 01:04:21,520
And so there's nothing very dramatic going on.

1131
01:04:21,520 --> 01:04:28,520
And so you might expect that if you dropped something through the horizon,

1132
01:04:28,520 --> 01:04:33,520
and now think about it in the frame of reference of the falling object,

1133
01:04:33,520 --> 01:04:39,520
the falling object doesn't say it took an infinite amount of time to go through.

1134
01:04:39,520 --> 01:04:42,520
Here's the falling object going through the horizon.

1135
01:04:42,520 --> 01:04:45,520
The clock ticks off seconds.

1136
01:04:45,520 --> 01:04:49,520
It took exactly seven seconds to go from here to here

1137
01:04:49,520 --> 01:04:51,520
in the frame of reference of the falling object.

1138
01:04:51,520 --> 01:04:53,520
The object says, I fell through,

1139
01:04:53,520 --> 01:04:58,520
or I fell past the point where I originally calculated there was a horizon.

1140
01:04:58,520 --> 01:05:01,520
He doesn't say, bump, I just felt the horizon.

1141
01:05:01,520 --> 01:05:05,520
But when it was outside the black hole,

1142
01:05:05,520 --> 01:05:08,520
he made a calculation of where the horizon was,

1143
01:05:08,520 --> 01:05:11,520
estimated how long it would take him to fall through it,

1144
01:05:11,520 --> 01:05:13,520
fell through it, nothing happened.

1145
01:05:13,520 --> 01:05:18,520
So from the point of view of somebody who falls through the horizon,

1146
01:05:19,520 --> 01:05:21,520
nothing happens at that point.

1147
01:05:21,520 --> 01:05:23,520
It sounds contradictory.

1148
01:05:23,520 --> 01:05:27,520
Either he does get burned up or he doesn't get burned up.

1149
01:05:27,520 --> 01:05:32,520
And if he doesn't get burned up, how did he avoid the consequences of this very, very high temperature?

1150
01:05:32,520 --> 01:05:35,520
Or it could be an atom.

1151
01:05:35,520 --> 01:05:37,520
Does the atom get ionized?

1152
01:05:37,520 --> 01:05:41,520
And if it does get ionized, do its particles get spread over the entire horizon

1153
01:05:41,520 --> 01:05:44,520
by the extremely high heat,

1154
01:05:44,520 --> 01:05:47,520
which causes things to diffuse?

1155
01:05:47,520 --> 01:05:49,520
Or does it fall through here?

1156
01:05:49,520 --> 01:05:50,520
There's got to be an answer.

1157
01:05:50,520 --> 01:05:51,520
It's one or the other.

1158
01:05:51,520 --> 01:05:53,520
It can't be both, right?

1159
01:05:55,520 --> 01:06:03,520
So I think one way of trying to get at this

1160
01:06:03,520 --> 01:06:08,520
is to think, to try to think as much as possible

1161
01:06:08,520 --> 01:06:12,520
in what I would call an Einsteinian kind of way,

1162
01:06:12,520 --> 01:06:15,520
or maybe it's a Heisenbergian kind of way,

1163
01:06:15,520 --> 01:06:19,520
to try to be operational about it.

1164
01:06:19,520 --> 01:06:23,520
To try to say, look,

1165
01:06:23,520 --> 01:06:28,520
let's see if we can prove or disprove

1166
01:06:28,520 --> 01:06:32,520
this or that by doing an experiment.

1167
01:06:32,520 --> 01:06:37,520
Now here's the kind of experiment that you might try to think about.

1168
01:06:37,520 --> 01:06:43,520
The temperature of this atom here increases as it falls down.

1169
01:06:43,520 --> 01:06:48,520
In fact, it gets very hot before it passes through the horizon.

1170
01:06:49,520 --> 01:06:53,520
It doesn't have to go through the horizon to get good and hot.

1171
01:06:53,520 --> 01:06:57,520
How hot does it have to get to ionize a hydrogen atom?

1172
01:06:57,520 --> 01:07:00,520
13 volts.

1173
01:07:00,520 --> 01:07:03,520
13 electron volts, right.

1174
01:07:03,520 --> 01:07:05,520
How hot is that?

1175
01:07:05,520 --> 01:07:06,520
3,000.

1176
01:07:06,520 --> 01:07:08,520
3,000 degrees, something like that?

1177
01:07:08,520 --> 01:07:10,520
Yeah, a few thousand degrees.

1178
01:07:10,520 --> 01:07:13,520
So at some point it reaches 3,000 degrees.

1179
01:07:13,520 --> 01:07:14,520
It's outside the horizon.

1180
01:07:14,520 --> 01:07:17,520
At that point, if all makes sense,

1181
01:07:17,520 --> 01:07:21,520
then it should get ionized.

1182
01:07:21,520 --> 01:07:25,520
And that's before it fell through.

1183
01:07:25,520 --> 01:07:28,520
Therefore, it ought to be able to send the signal back out,

1184
01:07:28,520 --> 01:07:32,520
or somebody stationed over here ought to be able to send the signal back out

1185
01:07:32,520 --> 01:07:36,520
and said the atom either did or didn't get ionized.

1186
01:07:36,520 --> 01:07:40,520
From one point of view, the atom ought to be able to say,

1187
01:07:40,520 --> 01:07:42,520
nothing's happening to me.

1188
01:07:42,520 --> 01:07:44,520
I'm falling freely through the horizon.

1189
01:07:44,520 --> 01:07:47,520
I'm within a certain distance of the horizon.

1190
01:07:47,520 --> 01:07:50,520
You told me the temperature was going to be 3,000 degrees,

1191
01:07:50,520 --> 01:07:52,520
but I don't feel a darn thing,

1192
01:07:52,520 --> 01:07:55,520
and I'm going to send out the message to you and tell you.

1193
01:07:55,520 --> 01:07:57,520
From the other point of view,

1194
01:07:57,520 --> 01:08:00,520
you've done a mathematical calculation which says that the temperature gets hot.

1195
01:08:00,520 --> 01:08:02,520
You've got a conflict, a real conflict.

1196
01:08:02,520 --> 01:08:08,520
So let's see if we can turn it into an experimental conflict.

1197
01:08:08,520 --> 01:08:15,520
In fact, before we do, I want to remind you of the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.

1198
01:08:15,520 --> 01:08:16,520
Okay.

1199
01:08:17,520 --> 01:08:23,520
And the reason is the logic that goes on here

1200
01:08:23,520 --> 01:08:27,520
and that is important in understanding this better

1201
01:08:27,520 --> 01:08:34,520
is very close to the logic that Heisenberg used.

1202
01:08:34,520 --> 01:08:36,520
What did Heisenberg say?

1203
01:08:36,520 --> 01:08:41,520
He said you can't measure both the position and velocity of a particle.

1204
01:08:41,520 --> 01:08:45,520
In fact, in some sense, it can't have both a position and a velocity.

1205
01:08:45,520 --> 01:08:47,520
It has one or the other.

1206
01:08:47,520 --> 01:08:49,520
Or you can measure one or the other.

1207
01:08:49,520 --> 01:08:55,520
If having a certain property means that that property can be measured,

1208
01:08:55,520 --> 01:08:58,520
then it has one or the other and not both.

1209
01:08:58,520 --> 01:08:59,520
And that seems contradictory.

1210
01:08:59,520 --> 01:09:01,520
Why does it seem contradictory?

1211
01:09:01,520 --> 01:09:07,520
If it makes sense to talk about the position of a particle at any time,

1212
01:09:07,520 --> 01:09:13,520
then it makes sense to talk about the sequence of positions of a particle.

1213
01:09:13,520 --> 01:09:17,520
If it makes sense to talk about the sequence of positions of a particle,

1214
01:09:17,520 --> 01:09:19,520
then it has a trajectory,

1215
01:09:19,520 --> 01:09:25,520
and that trajectory can be used to extrapolate and find the velocity for the particle.

1216
01:09:25,520 --> 01:09:30,520
So if it's really true that the particle has a position at every instant,

1217
01:09:30,520 --> 01:09:33,520
then how can it not have a velocity at every instant?

1218
01:09:33,520 --> 01:09:38,520
Heisenberg said, alright, I don't care what you say about whether it does or doesn't.

1219
01:09:38,520 --> 01:09:42,520
Let's ask if we can really measure both simultaneously.

1220
01:09:42,520 --> 01:09:46,520
And I just want to very quickly remind you of the logic here.

1221
01:09:46,520 --> 01:09:51,520
So supposing you have a particle, an electron,

1222
01:09:51,520 --> 01:09:56,520
and you want to measure its position to high precision.

1223
01:09:56,520 --> 01:09:58,520
You want to measure its position to high precision.

1224
01:09:58,520 --> 01:10:00,520
How do you do it?

1225
01:10:00,520 --> 01:10:01,520
You hit it with a photon.

1226
01:10:01,520 --> 01:10:03,520
You create an image of it on a screen.

1227
01:10:03,520 --> 01:10:10,520
And in order to have the resolving power to see the location of that electron

1228
01:10:10,520 --> 01:10:13,520
to within a resolution delta x,

1229
01:10:13,520 --> 01:10:15,520
you have to have a photon.

1230
01:10:15,520 --> 01:10:18,520
You have to hit it with a photon, or a light wave,

1231
01:10:18,520 --> 01:10:27,520
whose wavelength is no larger,

1232
01:10:27,520 --> 01:10:32,520
is less than or equal to delta x.

1233
01:10:32,520 --> 01:10:36,520
But then, if the wavelength is less than delta x,

1234
01:10:36,520 --> 01:10:39,520
that says that the momentum is larger of the photon,

1235
01:10:39,520 --> 01:10:45,520
is going to be larger or equal to Planck's constant over delta x.

1236
01:10:45,520 --> 01:10:51,520
Is that the Planck's constant with the cross or without the cross?

1237
01:10:51,520 --> 01:10:53,520
It doesn't matter.

1238
01:10:53,520 --> 01:10:58,520
That means that this particle is going to get bombarded by a photon

1239
01:10:58,520 --> 01:11:00,520
in order to measure it.

1240
01:11:00,520 --> 01:11:04,520
You might have said, look, I believe that particle is standing still.

1241
01:11:04,520 --> 01:11:09,520
I've created that particle in such a way that it's standing absolutely still.

1242
01:11:09,520 --> 01:11:13,520
And I want to confirm that it's standing absolutely still.

1243
01:11:13,520 --> 01:11:18,520
I want to confirm that it's standing absolutely still at the origin.

1244
01:11:18,520 --> 01:11:23,520
So what I will do is measure its position very quickly,

1245
01:11:23,520 --> 01:11:27,520
and then instantaneously afterwards measure its velocity

1246
01:11:27,520 --> 01:11:31,520
and try to check that it was both at the origin and at rest.

1247
01:11:31,520 --> 01:11:32,520
Well, you know the story.

1248
01:11:32,520 --> 01:11:34,520
I mean, the story is extremely well known.

1249
01:11:34,520 --> 01:11:36,520
I'm just reminding you of it.

1250
01:11:36,520 --> 01:11:42,520
That if you have to hit it with a particle of momentum p,

1251
01:11:42,520 --> 01:11:43,520
it's going to get hit.

1252
01:11:43,520 --> 01:11:44,520
It's going to recoil.

1253
01:11:44,520 --> 01:11:49,520
The particle is going to go off in some direction with a momentum more or less of order p.

1254
01:11:49,520 --> 01:11:50,520
In what direction?

1255
01:11:50,520 --> 01:11:54,520
Well, that direction is somewhat random.

1256
01:11:54,520 --> 01:11:59,520
And so if you try to measure the velocity afterwards,

1257
01:11:59,520 --> 01:12:02,520
it will not be what you thought it was in the first place.

1258
01:12:02,520 --> 01:12:07,520
In other words, the experiment creates exactly the condition

1259
01:12:07,520 --> 01:12:12,520
that it was designed to show wasn't the case.

1260
01:12:12,520 --> 01:12:20,520
The experiment was designed to show that the velocity was zero, let us say.

1261
01:12:20,520 --> 01:12:25,520
And just the experiment itself created the condition

1262
01:12:25,520 --> 01:12:32,520
which was the opposite of what it was designed to confirm.

1263
01:12:32,520 --> 01:12:33,520
That's the Heisenberg logic.

1264
01:12:33,520 --> 01:12:36,520
It's deeply, of course, connected with quantum mechanics.

1265
01:12:36,520 --> 01:12:39,520
H-bar appears in it.

1266
01:12:39,520 --> 01:12:41,520
In classical electrodynamics,

1267
01:12:41,520 --> 01:12:46,520
you can make an image with an arbitrarily small amount of,

1268
01:12:46,520 --> 01:12:51,520
an arbitrarily low intensity electromagnetic wave.

1269
01:12:51,520 --> 01:12:54,520
You don't have to have one whole quantum.

1270
01:12:54,520 --> 01:12:59,520
In quantum mechanics, you can't subdivide the energy less than a quantum.

1271
01:12:59,520 --> 01:13:02,520
